      <h1>HSA vs. FSA: Pre-Tax Healthcare Savings Compared</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 22, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>6 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">HSAs and FSAs are excellent tools for reducing your taxable income while saving for medical expenses. Here is a comparison of their key differences to help you choose the right account.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>The major difference:</strong> HSA funds roll over from year to year indefinitely, and the account is yours to keep even if you leave your job. FSA funds are generally "use-it-or-lose-it" and expire at the end of the year.</div>

      <h2>What is a Health Savings Account (HSA)?</h2>
      <p>An HSA is a tax-advantaged savings account available to individuals enrolled in a High-Deductible Health Plan (HDHP). Contributions are made pre-tax, growth is tax-free, and withdrawals are completely tax-free when used for qualified medical expenses. This is often referred to as the "triple tax advantage."</p>
      <p>Because your balances roll over annually, an HSA can double as an investment account, allowing you to grow your funds in index funds for retirement medical costs.</p>

      <h2>What is a Flexible Spending Account (FSA)?</h2>
      <p>An FSA is an employer-sponsored account that allows employees to set aside pre-tax dollars for medical, dental, and vision expenses. Unlike HSAs, you do not need to be enrolled in a specific health insurance plan to participate.</p>
      <p>The primary drawback of an FSA is the "use-it-or-lose-it" rule. If you do not spend your allocated funds by the end of the plan year (or during a brief grace period), the remaining balance is forfeited to your employer.</p>

      <h2>Key differences compared</h2>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Feature</th>
          <th>HSA</th>
          <th>FSA</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Insurance Requirement</td>
          <td>Must have an HDHP</td>
          <td>Any health plan</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Ownership</td>
          <td>Belongs to you</td>
          <td>Owned by employer</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Rollover Rules</td>
          <td>Full balance rolls over</td>
          <td>Use-it-or-lose-it (small rollover cap)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Investment Options</td>
          <td>Yes (stocks, mutual funds)</td>
          <td>No (interest-bearing only)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Contribution Source</td>
          <td>Pre-tax payroll or post-tax direct</td>
          <td>Pre-tax payroll only</td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <h2>Which account is right for you?</h2>
      <p>If you are relatively healthy, have low routine medical costs, and are enrolled in a High-Deductible Health Plan, the HSA is the superior choice due to its investment potential and portable ownership. If you have predictable annual medical expenses (such as prescription medications or dental work) and do not have an HDHP, the FSA is an excellent way to pay for those costs with tax-free dollars. Just be careful not to over-allocate funds to your FSA to avoid losing money at the end of the year.</p>
